## 4. Component Guidelines

For each component: semantic HTML/ARIA, keyboard behavior, screen reader expectations, motion notes, and ✅ Do / ❌ Don't examples.

---

### 4.1 Button

**Semantic HTML/ARIA**

- Use `<button type="button">` (or `type="submit"` in forms). Do not use `<div>` or `<span>` with click handlers for actions.
- Provide an accessible name: visible text or `aria-label` for icon-only buttons.
- For loading state: `aria-busy="true"` and optionally `aria-label` that includes the action and "loading" (e.g. "Save, loading").

**Keyboard**

- Focusable by default; activatable with **Enter** and **Space**.
- Focus order follows layout; visible focus ring (min 2px per policy config) using `:focus-visible`.

**Screen reader**

- Announce the button's label and state (e.g. "Save", "Delete, loading"). For destructive buttons in a confirmation flow, ensure the modal (not just the button) explains the consequence.

**Motion**

- If a loading spinner is used, respect `prefers-reduced-motion` (e.g. static "Loading" text when reduced motion is preferred).

**Examples**

- ✅ **Do:** `<button type="button" class="btn btn-primary" aria-label="Save">Save</button>`
- ✅ **Do:** `<button type="button" aria-label="Delete device" class="btn btn-destructive">Delete</button>` (then open confirmation modal)
- ❌ **Don't:** `<div role="button" tabindex="0" @click="save">Save</div>` — use `<button>`
- ❌ **Don't:** Icon-only button without `aria-label`: `<button><Icon name="trash" /></button>`

---

### 4.2 Modal (Dialog)

**Semantic HTML/ARIA**

- Use `role="dialog"` (or native `<dialog>` with correct support), `aria-modal="true"`, `aria-labelledby` pointing to the title, `aria-describedby` pointing to the body when present.
- Optional: `aria-labelledby` and `aria-describedby` on the dialog container so the first thing read is the title and description.

**Keyboard**

- **Focus trap:** When `focusTrapModals: true`, when the modal opens, move focus to the first focusable element inside the dialog (or the dialog container if no focusable element). **Tab** and **Shift+Tab** must cycle only through focusable elements **inside** the modal; focus must not leave until the modal is closed.
- **Escape** closes the modal and returns focus to the element that opened it (e.g. the "Delete" button).
- On close (Escape, Cancel, or Confirm), return focus to the trigger element.

**Screen reader**

- On open, the dialog is announced; title and description are read (via `aria-labelledby` / `aria-describedby`). User understands that context has changed to the dialog.

**Motion**

- If the modal uses an entrance animation, respect `prefers-reduced-motion` (e.g. skip or shorten animation).

**Examples**

- ✅ **Do:** Focus trap so Tab never leaves the dialog; on close, focus returns to trigger.
- ✅ **Do:** `<div role="dialog" aria-modal="true" aria-labelledby="dialog-title" aria-describedby="dialog-desc">` with visible title and description.
- ❌ **Don't:** Allow Tab to move focus to the page behind the modal.
- ❌ **Don't:** Close the modal without restoring focus to the trigger.

---

### 4.3 Table

**Semantic HTML/ARIA**

- Use `<table>`, `<thead>`, `<tbody>`, `<th>`, `<td>`. Use `scope="col"` on column headers; `scope="row"` on row headers if applicable.
- Optional `<caption>` or `aria-label` on the table for context.
- Ensure every cell is associated with its headers (implicit with correct scope, or `headers` attribute when needed).

**Keyboard**

- All action buttons in the table (e.g. Edit, Delete) must be focusable and activatable with Enter/Space. Tab order: left to right, row by row.

**Screen reader**

- Column headers are announced with cell content. Caption or table label provides context. Row actions (e.g. "Edit", "Delete") have clear accessible names.

**Motion**

- No specific motion requirements; follow global reduced-motion rule for any row animations.

**Examples**

- ✅ **Do:** `<th scope="col">Name</th>` and semantic `<table>` structure.
- ✅ **Do:** Per-row actions: `<button aria-label="Edit device">Edit</button>`, `<button aria-label="Delete device">Delete</button>` (Delete opens confirmation modal).
- ❌ **Don't:** Use `<div>` with grid layout for tabular data instead of `<table>`.
- ❌ **Don't:** Omit scope or headers so screen readers cannot associate cells with headers.

---

### 4.4 Agentic-Specific: Streaming / Progressively Revealed Content

**Semantic HTML/ARIA**

- Use an `aria-live` region (e.g. `aria-live="polite"`) for the container that receives streamed or progressively revealed text.
- Use `aria-busy="true"` while content is streaming; set to `false` when complete.
- Prefer **polite** so announcements do not interrupt the user; use **assertive** only for critical interruptions (e.g. "Error: connection lost").

**Keyboard**

- Do not steal focus as content streams. If the user is typing or focused in an input, keep focus there unless the design explicitly moves focus (e.g. to an error message).

**Screen reader**

- Streamed content should be announced as it appears (live region). Avoid announcing every character; batching or announcing by sentence/phrase reduces cognitive load. When streaming completes, ensure the final state is announced (e.g. "Response complete").

**Motion**

- If a "typing" or cursor animation is used, respect `prefers-reduced-motion`.

**Examples**

- ✅ **Do:** `<div aria-live="polite" aria-busy="true" aria-atomic="false">` for streaming text; set `aria-busy="false"` when done.
- ✅ **Do:** Optionally use `aria-atomic="true"` only when the entire message should be re-read on update (e.g. short status), not for long streaming text.
- ❌ **Don't:** Use `aria-live="assertive"` for normal streaming output.
- ❌ **Don't:** Change focus automatically as each token or line streams in.

---

### 4.5 Agentic-Specific: Long-Running Tasks and Progress

**Semantic HTML/ARIA**

- Use `role="progressbar"` with `aria-valuenow`, `aria-valuemin`, `aria-valuemax` when progress is determinate.
- For indeterminate progress: `role="status"` and `aria-live="polite"` with a label like "Loading…" or "Processing…".
- Provide a way to **cancel** or **stop** when safe: a button with an accessible name (e.g. "Cancel", "Stop") that is focusable and activatable by keyboard.

**Keyboard**

- Cancel/Stop must be in tab order and activatable with Enter/Space. Focus should not be trapped on the progress indicator; user can tab to Cancel.

**Screen reader**

- Progress is announced (e.g. "Progress 50%" or "Loading…"). When complete or cancelled, announce the result (e.g. "Complete", "Cancelled").

**Motion**

- Spinner or progress animation: respect `prefers-reduced-motion` (e.g. static "Loading" or minimal motion).

**Examples**

- ✅ **Do:** `<div role="progressbar" aria-valuenow="40" aria-valuemin="0" aria-valuemax="100" aria-label="Upload progress">`
- ✅ **Do:** Indeterminate: `<div role="status" aria-live="polite" aria-label="Agent is searching">` plus a "Cancel" button.
- ❌ **Don't:** Run a long task with no progress or cancel option and no status announcement.
- ❌ **Don't:** Use only a visual spinner with no `role="status"` or `aria-live` so screen readers get no feedback.

---

### 4.6 Agentic-Specific: Agent Actions and Status

**Semantic HTML/ARIA**

- Use a dedicated **status** or **log** region with `aria-live="polite"` (or `role="status"`) for agent activity (e.g. "Agent is searching", "Agent found 3 results", "Agent is updating the document").
- Use clear, concise language. Avoid jargon; prefer "Searching…" over "Running query."
- When the agent performs an action on the user's behalf, announce what was done (e.g. "Device deleted" or "Settings saved") in the same live region or via a toast that is accessible.

**Keyboard**

- Status text is typically not focusable; ensure critical follow-up actions (e.g. "Retry", "Undo") are focusable and in tab order.

**Screen reader**

- One primary live region for current agent status reduces confusion. Update the same region rather than creating many competing live regions.

**Motion**

- Follow global motion rules for any status animations.

**Examples**

- ✅ **Do:** Single live region: "Agent is searching." → "Found 3 results." → "Displaying results."
- ✅ **Do:** After agent action: "Device deleted. You can undo this in the next 5 seconds." with an accessible "Undo" button.
- ❌ **Don't:** Silently update the page (e.g. delete a row) with no announcement.
- ❌ **Don't:** Use multiple assertive live regions that interrupt each other.

---

## 5. Modal Focus Trap (Summary)

- When a modal is open, focus moves to the first focusable element inside the dialog (or the dialog container if nothing is focusable).
- Tab and Shift+Tab cycle only through focusable elements **inside** the modal.
- When the modal is closed (Escape, Cancel, or Confirm), focus returns to the element that opened the modal.
- This ensures keyboard users are not lost and screen reader users understand that the context has changed to the dialog.

---

## 6. Quick Reference for the Agent

When generating UI, the agent must:

- Use semantic HTML and ARIA per component guidelines (button, modal, table, streaming, progress, status).
- Ensure every interactive element has an accessible name and is keyboard operable.
- Apply modal focus trap for dialogs and restore focus on close (`focusTrapModals: true`).
- Use focus ring minimum width per config (`focusRingMinWidth: 2`).
- For destructive intent: generate a confirmation modal with title, description, and explicit Confirm/Cancel before executing.
- For streaming or long-running agent activity: expose status via `aria-live` / `role="status"` and provide cancel where appropriate.
- Respect `prefers-reduced-motion` per `reducedMotion: noScale` for non-essential motion.
- Use design token colors that meet WCAG 2.2 AA contrast.

Refer to component docs (`components/button.md`, `components/confirmation-modal.md`, `components/basic-modal.md`, `components/table.md`) for layout, variants, and token usage; this policy defines the accessibility requirements those components must satisfy.
